  "prompt": "What is the nicest library at Columbia to work at?",
  "response": "Columbia University has several beautiful and inspiring libraries, each with its own unique atmosphere. The \"nicest\" library for working depends on your preferences, but here are some of the top choices:\n\n1. **Butler Library**  \n   - The largest library on campus, Butler is a classic choice with its grand reading room, historic architecture, and ample study spaces. The **Butler Stacks** are particularly popular for quiet, focused work.\n\n2. **Avery Architectural & Fine Arts Library**  \n   - Known for its stunning design and natural light, Avery is a favorite among architecture and art students. The open spaces and aesthetic appeal make it a serene place to work.\n\n3. **Starr East Asian Library**  \n   - Located in Kent Hall, this library features a tranquil, meditative atmosphere with beautiful East Asian decor. It\u2019s quieter and less crowded, making it ideal for deep focus.\n\n4. **Lehman Library (formerly known as the Rare Book & Manuscript Library)**  \n   - This library offers a more intimate and scholarly environment, with access to rare collections. The reading rooms are elegant and conducive to concentrated work.\n\n5. **Barnard College\u2019s Milstein Center**  \n   - Just across the street from Columbia\u2019s main campus, Milstein is modern, bright, and inviting. It offers a variety of study spaces, including group rooms and individual carrels.\n\n6. **Northwest Corner Building Library**  \n   - A newer addition to the library system, this space is quiet, modern, and well-lit, with great views of the campus.\n\nIf you prefer a quiet, historic vibe, **Butler Library** or **Starr East Asian Library** might be your best bet. For a more modern and open environment, **Milstein Center** or **Northwest Corner Building Library** could be ideal. Each library has its own charm, so it\u2019s worth exploring a few to find your favorite!",
